    "lp_why": {
      "type": "aliange-lp-text-block",
      "settings": {
        "label": "Why It Matters",
        "headline": "Skin Responds to Systems",
        "body": "<p>Many skincare routines are assembled by combining products from multiple brands — each formulated independently, with different delivery systems, pH environments, and ingredient interactions.</p><p>While each product may be effective on its own, combining them without a structured formulation strategy can compromise the skin’s delicate biological balance.</p><h3>1. Ingredient Instability</h3><p>Many active ingredients are highly sensitive to their surrounding environment. Changes in pH or formulation conditions can destabilise peptides, antioxidants, and other bioactive compounds, reducing their effectiveness before they can benefit the skin.</p><h3>2. Barrier Disruption</h3><p>Layering multiple strong actives without the correct supporting lipids and barrier-repair ingredients can weaken the skin barrier. This increases transepidermal water loss and triggers low-grade inflammation — a process increasingly recognised as a contributor to premature skin ageing.</p><h3>3. Inefficient Delivery</h3><p>For active ingredients to produce meaningful results, they must reach viable skin cells within the epidermis. Effective skincare requires carefully engineered delivery systems that allow ingredients to penetrate the stratum corneum and interact with living skin tissue.</p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p>",
        "bg": "white",
        "width": "narrow",
        "cta_text": "",
        "cta_url": "",
        "image": "shopify://shop_images/Generated_Image_March_23_2026_-_9_59PM.jpg",
        "image_position": "right"
      }
    },
